consent:
Interview Consent Form for Computational Workflow Study

UBC CS - Research Proposal for Ethics ID#H23-00382



Principal Investigator: Thomas Pasquier, PhD Associate Professor UBC Computer Science tjfmp@cs.ubc.ca 

Co-Investigator: Nichole Boufford MSc Student UBC Computer Science ncbouf@cs.ubc.ca 



Invitation

You are being invited to take part in this research study because you have indicated that you are interested in participating in our research study. Purpose This study uses different provenance representations to guide the user in answering questions about a not seen before workflow. We are interested in understanding the benefits and drawbacks of using a graph-based representation and a report-based representation to present an experimental workflow.



Study Procedures

Pre-Activity Questionnaire (5 minutes) You will be given a questionnaire to fill out before the study activity.

Introduction and Overview (10 minutes) You will be given an introduction to the study and you will watch a video demonstration of the user tool.

Activity (30 minutes) You will be shown an interface representing an experimental workflow and you will use the interface to answer questions about the workflow while thinking out loud. This part of the session will be screen and audio recorded. You will repeat this task with one more workflow and a different experimental workflow representation.

Post-Activity Questionnaire (10 minutes) After the activity, you will complete a brief questionnaire, and answer any follow-up questions from the investigator.



Potential Risks

There is minimal risk to participating in this study. If you disclose any information you later wish to remove from the study, you can let us know at any time.



Potential Benefit

You learn about workflow analysis and will help to design a tool that might help data scientists to track experiments.



Confidentiality 

Your confidentiality will be respected. Any information that could identify you as a participant in this study will be kept confidential. Any personal data and recorded data that may reveal your identity will be removed. Personal data will not be released without your consent unless required by law. Any identifying information will be changed; for example, each subject will be assigned a study number, such as Participant #1 or Participant #2 or a pseudonym. Information that directly discloses your identity will remain only with the Principal Investigator and/or designate. Computer files will be password-protected and encrypted on a password-protected computer and all digital audio and computer interaction files will be deleted after 5 years.



Screen-recording and audio recording

The activity portion of the study will be screen and audio recording. The investigator will start and stop the recording for the participant.



Remuneration/Compensation

Participants will be compensated one $15 Amazon Gift Card for completing the session.



Use of Study Information

This study is part of a graduate research project and will be used in a dissertation. Data may be analyzed for academic publication and published in an anonymized and/or aggregated form. Anonymized data may be used for academic presentations on the publication.



Open Access 

Some of the journals or conferences that we may publish our results with may require open access to data. Open access means that the publication and data may be made available to the public. If it is required for us to publish our data, it will be in summary form with identifying information removed. No recordings will be published. However, any open access publication may still increase the risk that some of the published data is associated with you. Once the data is made available, you will not be able to withdraw your data.



Contact for information about the study:

If you have any questions, concerns, or desire for further information about this part of the study before or during participation, you may contact Dr. Thomas Pasquier at tjfmp@cs.ubc.ca.

 

Contact for concerns about the rights of research subjects: If you have any concerns or complaints about your rights as a research participant and/or your experiences while participating in this study, contact the Research Participant Complaint Line in the UBC Office of Research Ethics at 604-822-8598 or if long distance e-mail RSIL@ors.ubc.ca or call toll free 1-877-822-8598.



Consent 

Your participation in this study is entirely voluntary and you may refuse to participate or withdraw from the study at any time without jeopardy to your employment. If you choose to withdraw from the study, your data will be deleted.



Selecting "I consent" indicates that you consent to participate in this study. If you do not consent please close the browser.

t3_q_2: The first execution was to edit the code in the train_model.py script and the second execution was to train a model using the train_model.py script.
post_0_0: The graph was confusing and overwhelming. The text was clear and straight forward, and directly allowed me to answer the questions being asked.
post_1_0: I felt there was a more logical flow of information, and I was much more efficiently able to seek out the answers to the questions.
post_2: Integrating code executions into text summaries so I can follow along with instructions by directly clicking and executing scripts.
post_3: If it was confusing and not very helpful or if it used terminology/concepts that I am unfamiliar with.

t3_q_2: First execution is initializing model environment and the second execution is the model code being executed in vim editor.
post_0_0: The text was slightly more useful for answering the questions because the descriptions required less inuition and inference to answer the questions compared to the graphs.
post_1_0: The graph was visually easier to interpret for a general idea of the model workflow however the text was enjoyable for deciphering the details of the model execution. Both were enjoyable to use.
post_2: I would like to use this tool during the development of my experiment to track and visualize my workflow. It would be nice to have the outputs be compatible with Git version control. I would also like to be able to use this tool across multiple platforms during the same project.
post_3: If there was a lack of documentation for the tool I would be less likely to use it or if it was incompatible with certain programs.

t3_q_2: The second execution of the training model is based on an updated script. The second execution also writes a script that can be used later for execution.
post_0_0: I felt that the text one was a higher level summary and helped answer questions in a more directed way.
post_1_0: The graph provided more indepth analysis if you wanted it.
post_2: Highlighting of linked routes (when you hover over an item it shows all the related items). Lay summaries in the graph representation. Having different visual encodings for the arrows of the graph to show read, write, load, in an easier manner. For both, having the ability to have hierarchical drop down tree to help organize larger amounts of data. Direct query interaction.

t3_q_2: the same for the first 4 steps, the second execution has an additional 5th "write" step.
post_0_0: Ok so Im biased because I really like graphs in general - I found graph much more helpful than text. The graph has explicit verbs for "read", "load", "write" that where harder to parse in the text summary version. I imagine color-coding key verbs in the text summary version could grant the affordances of the graph version (easier to spot).
post_1_0: Graph is better in my opinion because of color coding, meaningful axis (vertical meaning as a timeseries, horizontal meaning in filepath navigation - so you have 2D information instead of 1D timeline only).
post_2: Ctrl+F for sure, panning and zooming of the graph, integration with git would be phenomenal. This tool is almost like a visualization for forensic timeline.
post_3: Probably overhead, how automatic installation of this system would be for my own workflow. This is where git integration (as inspiration) would go, because for git you have to prepare your workflow ahead of using git, so I imagine this system would require a similar "workflow tidiness".
post_4: loved it! LOTS of vis research potential here (eyes emoji)

t3_q_2: The first execution was edited using the Vim editor and then opened again.
post_0_0: I spent less time trying to find the information when looking at mostly graph provenances.
post_1_0: It was less stressful to use mostly graph provenance because you can easily find the information.

t3_q_2: the data file was edited between the two executions
post_0_0: Text reads more like a storyline, which is more intuitive for me- the figures still required some background knowledge to understand, which I didn't always feel like I had
post_1_0: I felt more enjoyment when I felt like I had a better understanding, and the text summary supported my understanding
post_2: Both text and visualizations side by side- especially if the visualizations are consistent so that I could eventually learn how to read them with some practice.
post_3: Depends on how long it would take to set up- if set up would slow me down a lot, I might be less likely to use it.
post_4: This was challenging, but an interesting way of refreshing my experience with this kind of thing

post_0_0: The graph format was easier to read quickly and made it easier to identify relationships between different components. The text format felt more useful in identifying the workflow steps in order.
post_1_0: The graphs were more interesting to look at and seemed to show more information than the text.

pre_4_3_TEXT: Background in engineering and masters in GIS
t3_q_2: The second execution of trained_model.py was a different version than the first and resulted in a model output called model.ckpt.
post_0_0: In the practice questions where both graph and text summaries were available, there was some language in the text summary that was helpful in answering the questions. Otherwise, the graph summaries were most helpful.
post_1_0: The visual order of the graphs was very helpful and it was easier to see repeated steps and patterns. The text summary tended to jump around more and was difficult to follow. A lot of the steps (such as loading the libraries) needed to be repeated, which was distracting when trying to extract information.
post_2: I think an R Markdown type document (Jupyter notebook) that shows the executable steps one by one could be tied to the code.Text should be self-referential and allow the suer to easily jump between different steps without having to search too hard. Plain or natural language commentary is always useful. Where there intermediate outputs that aren't critical to the overall flow of the experiment, nest them on a different page to keep them from being distracting. Allow the user to "zoom in" on different parts of the experiment (big picture vs small details and choices).
post_3: Complexity of the setup process - is it easily integrated with the code I have already written? Does it have good version control? Are there options for automating the process of describing it verbally? Are there tutorials on how to use it? Cost and security. Shareability of the output (view vs edit vs comment).

t3_q_2: The first execution was run without changing the script file, however for the second execution, some changes were made to the script file before execution.
post_0_0: The graph helped in understanding the flow of the execution while the text helped in understanding what was being done more elaborately. However the majority of the understanding came from the graph and the text was just acting like a support.
post_1_0: Graph, because very less wordings to read and remember, and the flow of the graph helps to understand the process faster as compared to the test where you need to read through each sentence and remember what is being done at each step. Also revisiting the graph is much easier and just eyeballing helps in understanding the overall flow.
post_4: Had fun using the graph to answer the questions.

post_1_0: Nobody wants to decipher a wall of text.

post_3: Ease of generation? If a simple tool exists, I would be likely to use it.
